{{Infobox court case |name = Christian Lawyers Association v Minister of Health |court = [[Transvaal Provincial Division]] |image = |imagesize = |imagelink = |imagealt = |caption = |full name = Christian Lawyers Association of SA and Others v Minister of Health and Others |date decided = {{Start date|1998|07|10|df=y}} |citations = 1998 (11) BCLR 1434 (T), 1998 (4) SA 1113 (T) |transcripts = |judges = McCreath J |number of judges = 1 |decision by = |prior actions = |appealed from = |appealed to = |subsequent actions = |related actions = |opinions = |keywords = |italic title = force }} '''''Christian Lawyers Association v Minister of Health''''' is a case in which the [[Transvaal Provincial Division]] of the [[High Court of South Africa]] ruled on the constitutionality of the [[Choice on Termination of Pregnancy Act]], the law which governs [[abortion in South Africa]]. The Christian Lawyers Association claimed that abortion violates [[Section Eleven of the Constitution of South Africa|section 11]] of the [[Constitution of South Africa|Constitution]], which provides that "Everyone has the right to life." The government noted an exception (a [[demurrer]]) on the grounds that constitutional rights do not apply to fetuses and that there was therefore no case to answer. The court accepted the government's argument and the case was dismissed.
